# Description

The LangGraph structure is the brain of the entire system. It orchestrates all agents in a state machine, replacing disconnected functions with a unified, stateful pipeline.

## Why LangGraph (vs. a Linear Pipeline with Callbacks)

LangGraph was chosen over a traditional linear pipeline for several reasons:

- **Shared typed state** — All agents read from and write to a single `GraphState` `TypedDict`, eliminating the need to manually pass data through function arguments.
- **Built-in retry logic** — Individual nodes can be retried independently without restarting the entire pipeline.
- **Parallel execution** — The Extractor agent runs one instance per source simultaneously via `Send()`, reducing latency by approximately **40%** for a 5-source query.
- **Checkpointing** — `MemorySaver` provides automatic state persistence, enabling pause/resume functionality and easier debugging.
- **Conditional branching** — Nodes can dynamically choose the next step (e.g., skipping the FactChecker when no contradictions are detected).
- **Native streaming** — LangGraph streams node outputs directly to Streamlit, allowing users to monitor agent progress in real time.

---

## Agent Execution Order

The pipeline follows the workflow defined in the project plan.

```text
Planner
    │
    ▼
Researcher
    │
    ▼
Extractor (parallel per source)
    │
    ▼
FactChecker
    │
    ▼
Reasoning
    │
    ▼
Teacher
```

Unlike a purely sequential pipeline, the **Extractor** executes one instance per source in parallel rather than processing sources one after another.

